Halliburton’s refreshed valuation work now points to a fair value of US$41.64, up from US$39.30, reflecting the latest modeling of the stock’s potential. This shift sits alongside a busy period of analyst activity, with several firms lifting price targets by US$1 to US$8, a new upgrade, and at least one cut, all shaping how you might think about the current risk and reward. Read on to see what is driving these moves and how you can track the evolving narrative from here.
Analyst Price Targets don't always capture the full story. Head over to our Company Report to find new ways to value Halliburton.
A cluster of firms including Jefferies, Barclays, Citi, Morgan Stanley, JPMorgan, Stifel, UBS, Susquehanna, Piper Sandler and BMO Capital have lifted price targets by between US$1 and US$8, which signals a constructive stance on Halliburton’s execution and prospects.
The larger moves, such as the US$8 target increases at Jefferies and Barclays and US$7 rises at Citi and Stifel, suggest these firms see enough support in their models to justify meaningfully higher valuation estimates compared with prior work.
Griffin Securities shifted to an upgrade, which adds an additional positive datapoint to the recent stream of target revisions and indicates increased confidence in how Halliburton is delivering against expectations.
Barclays also cut its target by US$1 in early April, reminding you that views are not uniformly positive and that some analysts see valuation or execution risks worth reflecting in their numbers.
The mix of frequent revisions, including both raises and at least one reduction, highlights that forecasts for Halliburton still carry uncertainty, so you should treat any single target as one input rather than a definitive guide to future returns.
